Koteshwar Mahadev Temple is a Hindu temple dedicated to Shiva, and is located approximately 3 kilometres (3,000 m) from the centre of the Rudraprayag district of Uttarakhand, a little above the Alaknanda River

Image Source:- Koteshwar Mahadev Temple Rudraprayag - How to Reach Koteshwar Temple

The location is presumed to be the spot where Lord Shiva had stopped for meditation on his way to Kedarnath. According to local mythology the temple has existed since the time of Bhasmasura. This was the demon who turned to ashes anyone whose head he touched. Lord Shiva went into hiding to escape this threat, resting in various places before coming to the cave at Koteshwar Mahadev. Shiva rested here for some time, meditating, before confronting and defeating the demon. A similar legend is associated with Shrikhand Mahadev and Kinner Kailash in Himachal Pradesh.

Source:- Koteshwar Mahadev - Wikipedia

Patal Bhubneshwar is one of the popular cave temple in Uttarakhand. Patal Bhubneshwar is one of the most mysterious and spiritual place of Uttarakhand. Why is the Uttarakhand government taking over temple control?

Uttarakhand is proud of being home to both - Shaiv and Vaishnav seats of Sanatan faith and that alone has helped it earn DevBhumi name.

But there are few basic facts that need to be factored in here, which - always on dope- SwarmyArmy can’t understand!

First things first: management of Sri Badrinath Ji & Sri Kedarnath Ji temples is currently done by a temple committee called Badri Kedar Temple Committee with a CEO (appointed by Govt - from admin services) and members appointed by Govt from local areas & eminent personalities

Uttarakhand is proud of being home to both - Shaiv and Vaishnav seats of Sanatan faith and that alone has helped it earn DevBhumi name.

But there are few basic facts that need to be factored in here, which - always on dope- SwarmyArmy can’t understand!

First things first: management of Sri Badrinath Ji & Sri Kedarnath Ji temples is currently done by a temple committee called Badri Kedar Temple Committee with a CEO (appointed by Govt - from admin services) and members appointed by Govt from local areas & eminent personalities

This system is in place since days of TehriRaja & was institutionalised in late 1930s with later amendments. Other two temples of Maa Gangotri Ji & Maa Yamunotri Ji are managed by local temple committees with members of Semwals (Maa Gangotri temple) & Uniyals (Maa Yamunotri temple)

Current CEO of BKTC is an IFS Officer - Shri BP Singh, totally committed and devoted man from nearby Mana Village. Just by his commitment and dedication, he is earned a place that irrespective of who comes to power, he remains CEO and all coz of his work ethic.

There is a panchayat system in place whereby priests- known as Haq Haqook dhari- get to discharge their religious duties (they can’t touch deity) every year on rotation basis. Part of yearly proceeds is shared with these families & present act is continuing with this system.

Along with Sri Badrinath Ji and Sri Kedarnath Ji, Uttarakhand is home to 4 Badri temples (part of PanchBadri) and 4 Kedar temples (part of PanchKedar). Current focus is only on Sri Badrinath Ji and Sri Kedarnath Ji and result is that majority is unaware of that.

New system seeks to bring all temples under the ambit on one common committee or board so that facilites around those temples can be expanded and more and more people get to visit them. There is also a need to reduce the pressure on few temples as more n more devotees are coming

In no case, Govt is trying to usurp rights of priests (known as Haq Haqook) and same is continued as before. Ditto is the case with Maa Gangotri and Maa Yamunotri temples where Govt has brought this under board by expanding the arrangement of BKTC to other temples

Also important to note is -my oft repeated argument - that temples of Uttarakhand, unlike South are not wealthy, nor were they seat of power. In case of South, Rajas used to rule on behalf of deity and that was never the case for Utkd where temples were purely religious practices only

And while system of BKTC is working fine, but there was felt a need to expand it to other temples for-

1) Readying them for more devotees by providing matching facilities

2) Organising the temple management such that best practises of BKTC are expanded to other temples

Unfortunately greed of very few is also responsible for this change in process of management of temples

While administration of temples by Shrine board route is NOT the best of the solutions but given the way temples are managed by teertha- Purohits; we do need to reform the way our temples are run currently

All those opposing formation of Shrine Board in Uttarakhand for management of temples would do well to ask all the devotees who recently visited CharDhaams about their experience of darshan....One of the single biggest reason for people moving away from Dharma is the greed of those responsible for acting as a bridge between the devotee and the Divine......and no one can claim to have ever escaped that greed of teertha- Purohits in our temples..

Only few castes of Uttarakhand hold rights to act as Pujaris at our Chaardhams: Uniyals for Yamunotri, Semwals for Gangotri, Dimris for Badrinath jee and Bagwaris-Semwals and dew other castes for Kedarnath. They don’t let any other castes work as Pujaris there & have monopoly.That system was working perfectly fine till the no of devotees visiting these temples was in hundreds or thousands - but now when the devotees nos have touched several lakhs, the Pujari castes is limited to those few castes only - thus creating a huge demand supply gap

Until a better, more effective and efficient system of temple administration is devised and more importantly our purohit samaj give up their greed, we will have to live with the system that can do more good for temple administration and dharma protection.

The system devised by Uttarakhand Govt is actually modelled on the Mata Vaishno Devi Shrine Board only and govt is committed to protecting the interests of the purohit samaj. On their part, pujaris, Purohits and Pandaas will do well to give up their greed and work for Dharma

Tungnath temple, at an altitude of 3680 Mtrs, is considered to be the highest temple of Lord Shiva and is one of the Panch (Five) Kedars. Madhmaheshwar, Tungnath, Rudranath, and Kalpnath with Kedarnath form the Panch Kedar and considered as the five most important temples of Lord Shiva in Garhwal Himalayas.

Tungnath Temple is located at a trekking distance of 3.5 km from Chopta and comes under the Rudraprayag district of Uttarakhand. Chandrashilla peak is further 1.5 km ahead of the temple. The altitude of Tungnath Temple is 3,680 Mtrs or 11,220 Feet and that of Chopta is 2600 Mtrs or 7,925 Feet. Chandrashilla Peak is further ahead at an altitude of 4,000 Mtrs or 12,192 Feet.

The best time to travel or visit Tungnath Temple is in April – November (exclude monsoon). In winters i.e December – February, when the snowfall starts the Tungnath becomes inaccessible. Soon, Chopta also gets snowbound and gets cut-off from the rest of the valley.

Monsoon season is generally not a suggested time period to visit the region of Chopta – Tungnath – Chandrashilla – Deori Tal due to landslides which are common in Uttarakhand

Reach to Tungnath and Chopta

By Air

The nearest airport is Jolly Grant, Bhaniawala, Dehradun, 41 km from Haridwar. After reaching Haridwar, you need to carry the rest of the journey by road only. Haridwar to Chopta is about 225 km by road.

By Rail

The nearest railway station is at Haridwar. After reaching Haridwar you need to carry the rest of the journey by road only. Haridwar to Chopta is about 225 km by road.

By Road

Delhi – Haridwar (212 km) – Rishikesh – Dev Prayag – Srinagar – Rudra Prayag (take left towards Kedarnath) – Agustmuni – Syal Saur – Kund – Ukhimath – Duggalbitta – Baniya Kund – Chopta (448 km) – Tungnath – Chandrashilla

Vehicles can go up to Chopta only, and you need to trek about 3.5 km from Chopta to reach Tungnath. If you are interested in Chandrashilla, you need to trek about 1.5 km from Tungnath further to reach the Chandrashilla peak. There is no motorable road to Tungnath and Chandrashilla.

Have you ever been to the Tungnath temple in the Chandrashila peak, Uttarakhand?
Originally Answered: Have you ever been to Tungnath temple, the chandrashila peak Uttarakhand?

Yes I have been there and it is not too difficult to get there. You need to drive up to Chopta and then take a trek. The trek is pretty steep though fairly short. Most people take a mule one way going up, which is a good idea as the path is steep. Chandrashila is about a kilometer from Tungnath. The trek is short but again very steep and often takes longer than expected due to the altitude which touches 4k meters. Once at Chardrashila you get a spectacular view of the Himalayan snow peaks with a 360 degree view and almost all the major peaks are visible from this point.

The Trek from Chopta to

Yes I have been there and it is not too difficult to get there. You need to drive up to Chopta and then take a trek. The trek is pretty steep though fairly short. Most people take a mule one way going up, which is a good idea as the path is steep. Chandrashila is about a kilometer from Tungnath. The trek is short but again very steep and often takes longer than expected due to the altitude which touches 4k meters. Once at Chardrashila you get a spectacular view of the Himalayan snow peaks with a 360 degree view and almost all the major peaks are visible from this point.

The Trek from Chopta to Tungnath is about 4 kms but the height gain in the 4km is more than 700 meters in the short stretch. You gain another about 400 meters in the 1 km trek to Chndrashila from Tungnath.

If planning a trip, you need to spend a night at Chopta so you can acclimatize to the altitude and then start climbing early in the morning to reach Chardrashila at Sunrise so you can see the spectacular view as the sun is rising.

Chopta doesn’t have very good hotels or resthouses, but basic accommodation is available and you may even get hot water on request at some of them. There are several dhaba style food shacks that serve hot food and tea etc.

Tungnath is the highest Shiva Temple and one of the Panch Kedars. Yes, it is higher than Kedarnath in elevation.

Why is the Kedarnath Temple in Uttarakhand so famous?

Kedarnath temple, located in uttrakhand in the Himalayas, is 3583 metres above the sea level on the shores of Mandakini river.

It is the most remote shrine of the chota char dham sites.

Kedarnath is surrounded by the majestic mountains, and due to its extreme weather these mountains are clad with snow for most of the year and is open for only 8 months from April to November.

Kedarnath temple, located in uttrakhand in the Himalayas, is 3583 metres above the sea level on the shores of Mandakini river.

It is the most remote shrine of the chota char dham sites.

Kedarnath is surrounded by the majestic mountains, and due to its extreme weather these mountains are clad with snow for most of the year and is open for only 8 months from April to November.

So coming back to your question why is the Kedarnath temple so famous?

Mythologically speaking, Kedarnath temple was built by the pandava brothers, after the Kurukshetra war to seek forgiveness for killing their kin during the war.

But lord Shiva did not want to forgive them, so he turned itno a bull and hid among cattle on the hill.

So Bhima, one brother among pandavas managed to find him, and he grabbed his tail and pleaded to Shiva to appear before them and forgive them.

On being found by the pandavas, lord shiva dove underground and Bhim could only manage to get hold of his hump and mythologically, other parts of the body of the bull showed up at 5 different places.

And after that lord shiva forgave pandavas and they then built a temple there, which is today famous by the name Kedarnath temple.

Other than the history, Kedarnath temple is also famous for the devotion offered by the lord Shiva devotees.

Devotees every year manage to visit the temple after commuting 14 kilometres just to see the glimpses of Lord shiva.

Surkanda Devi Temple is dedicated to Goddess Parvati. This temple is one of the 51 Shakti Peeth located all over the Indian subcontinent and also a part of the popular Devi Darshan triangle that includes Chandrabadni and Kunjapuri.

According to the mythology, the origins of the Surkanda Devi temple can be attributed to Goddess Sati, wife of Lord Shiva who immolated herself in her father Daksha's sacrifice when he embarrassed Shiva by not inviting the couple to the Yajna. When Shiva was passing over this place on his way back to Kailash carrying Sati's body, her head fell at the spot where the modern temple of Surkhanda Devi stands and due to which the temple's got its name as sirkhanda which overtime is now called surkanda.

Perched at an altitude of about 2756 m, the temple is famous for its architectural beauty and offers a 360-degree view of the surrounding region along with the snowy Himalayan peaks. Also, it commands a beautiful view of Dehra Dun, Rishikesh, Chandrabadni, Pratapnagar, and Chakrata. Flowers of varied kinds and indigenous herbs are grown in abundance here and some of the beautiful birds of the western Himalayas are also found in the neighborhood.

At a distance of 9 km from Dhanaulti and 35 km from Mussoorie. Surkanda Devi temple demands a trek of about 2 km trek from the village of Kaddukhal. The trekking path is well paved and takes about 30 minutes one way. Tourists can also reach the temple by walking along an 8 km trek path amidst the dense forests from Dhanaulti. Hence, it is also a popular attraction among trekkers.

Surkhananda Devi Fair is celebrated on the eve of Ganga Dussehra at the temple. The festival is celebrated in the month of May/June every year and attracts a large number of devotees.

Why Mahasu Devta Temple is very famous in Uttarakhand?

A famous temple situated in the lap of nature is 'Mahasu Devta'. It is believed that whoever asks here with a sincere heart that Mahasu Devta fulfils his wishes.

It is interesting that salt is presented to Rashtrapati Bhavan from Delhi every year here. This temple, adorned by mixed-style architecture, is 190 km from Dehradun and 156 km from Mussoorie. The temple is located on the eastern spur of the Tons River in Hanol village near Chakrata.

The secret of a stream of water in the womb

Devotees are not allowed in the sanctum sanctorum of Mahasu Devta's temple. Only the priest of the temple can enter the temple. This thing is still a mystery today. There is always a flame burning in the temple which has been burning for decades.

A stream of water also comes out in the sanctum sanctorum of the temple, but where it goes, where it comes out is unknown.

Actually 'Mahasu Devta' is the collective name of not one but four deities and in the local language, Mahasu is a corruption of the word 'Mahashiva'. The names of the four Mahasu brothers are Basik Mahasu, Pabasik Mahasu, Buthia Mahasu (Botha Mahasu) and Chalda Mahasu, which are the same forms of Lord Shiva.

Court also considered this temple

The Mahasu deity is worshipped in Uttarkashi in Uttarkashi, the entire Jaunsar-Bawar region, Rwai Pargana as well as Himachal Pradesh's Sirmaur, Solan, Shimla, Bishahar and Jubbal.

In these areas, Mahasu Devta is considered as the god of justice and the temple as a court. Presently devotees of Mahasu Devta plead for justice in the temple which is fulfilled by them.

Mahasu had won Hanol's temple

This temple was built in the 9th century. The temple is currently under the patronage of the Archaeological Survey Department (ASI). The Mahasu deity is the form of Lord Bholenath. It is also believed that Mahasu won this temple of Hanol on any condition. The Mahasu god is Jaunsar Bawar, the Isht Dev of Himachal Pradesh and Uttarakhand.
